Subject: EXCLUSIVE: Alleged Misuse of Public Funds at Top Film School Threatens Korea's International Education Goals

Dear Editor,

I am writing to share urgent findings regarding potential misuse of public funds at Dongguk University connected to misrepresented international partnerships. Our investigation has uncovered evidence that raises serious questions about institutional accountability and transparency at one of Korea's premier educational institutions. These issues threaten Korea's higher education sector and national education goals if left unaddressed.

KEY FINDINGS:

1. **Potential Misrepresentation of International Partnerships**:
   - Our verification process found at least one officially denied partnership (Canadian university) out of Dongguk's claimed 381 partnerships
   - Such partnerships directly impact government funding allocations to universities
   - This raises questions about proper oversight of public education funds
   - Our Korean-language reporting on this angle has received substantial engagement from concerned citizens, government official and film festival organizers: https://x.com/Gender_Watchdog/status/1918201577363652788

2. **International Partners Taking Action**:
   - Multiple North American universities have begun reviewing their relationships with Dongguk University
   - Three U.S. universities have committed to "reviewing partnerships" citing compliance concerns
   - A Canadian university has publicly denied partnership claims made by Dongguk
   - A global university ranking organization has escalated these concerns to senior management

3. **Dual Communication Systems Raise Transparency Concerns**:
   - Our investigation uncovered a troubling "dual-face" communication strategy:
     • English-language faculty directories list official institutional emails (professor@dongguk.edu)
     • Korean-language directories list personal Gmail/Naver accounts for the same professors
     • Many institutional email addresses shown to international partners are non-functional
   - This pattern exists across multiple departments and creates barriers to proper accountability
   - Example: Professor Jean-Hun Chung is listed as jhchung@dongguk.edu (non-functional) on the English site but evengates@gmail.com on the Korean site

